{"cursor":"9066","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Religious vows' are the public vows made by the members of religious\ncommunities pertaining to their conduct, practices and views.\n\nIn the Buddhist tradition, in particular within the Mahayana and Vajrayana\ntradition, many different kinds of religious vows are taken by the lay community\nas well as by the monastic community, as they progress along the path of\npractice. In the monastic tradition of all schools of Buddhism the Vinaya\nexpounds the vows of the fully ordained Nuns and Monks.\n\nIn the Christian tradition, such public vows are made by the religious life â\ncenobitic and eremitic â of the Roman Catholic, Anglican, and Eastern Orthodox\nChurches, whereby they confirm their public profession of the Evangelical\nCounsels or Benedictine equivalent. They are regarded as the individual's free\nresponse to a call by God to follow Jesus Christ more closely under the action\nof the Holy Spirit in a particular form of religious living. A person who lives\na religious life according to vows they have made is called a 'votary' or a\n'votarist'. The religious vow, being a public vow, is binding in Church law. One\nof its effects is that the person making it ceases to be free to marry. In the\nRoman Catholic Church, by making a religious vow â whether as a member of a\nreligious community or as a consecrated hermit â one does not become a member of\nthe hierarchy but becomes a member of a unique state of life which is neither\nClerical nor Lay, the Consecrated\nState. [http://www.intratext.com/IXT/ENG0017/_P1X.HTM 1983 Code of Canon\nLaw, Canon 588] Nevertheless, many male members of the Consecrated life\nare members of the hierarchy, because they are in Holy Orders. [http://www.-\nwebcitation.org/query?url=http://uk.geocities.com/deo_auxiliante%40btinternet.c-\nom/churchchart.html&date=2009-10-25+04:14:48 Chart showing the place of those\nmaking religious vows among the People of God] The members of some Roman\nCatholic communities make \"recognized private vows\", which must not be confused\nwith private vows but are similar to public vows in Church law.\n","linknr":235,"url":"Religious_vows","recorded":1371237448,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Religious_vows&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Religious_vows&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Vows","/wiki/Consecrated_life","/wiki/Cenobium","/wiki/Hermit","/wiki/Catholic_Church","/wiki/Anglican_Communion","/wiki/Eastern_Orthodox_Church","/wiki/Evangelical_Counsels","/wiki/Rule_of_St_Benedict","/wiki/Jesus","/wiki/Christ","/wiki/Holy_Spirit","/wiki/Christian_monasticism","/wiki/Church_law","/wiki/Cenobium","/wiki/Hermit","/wiki/Catholic_Church_hierarchy","/wiki/Catholic_Church_hierarchy#The_Clergy","/wiki/Catholic_Church_hierarchy#Laity","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Consecrated_life","/wiki/Catholic_Church_hierarchy","/wiki/Holy_Orders","#cite_note-2","#In_the_western_church","#In_the_Roman_Catholic_Church_today","#In_the_Eastern_Orthodox_Church","#References","#External_links","/w/index.php?title=Religious_vows&action=edit&section=1","/wiki/Monk","/wiki/Nun","/wiki/Rule_of_Saint_Benedict","/wiki/Profession_(religious)#Religious_profession","#cite_n